The paper proposes a deep-learning based workflow for in situ data processing using autoencoders, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of autoencoders for data compression and reduction also involves computer vision (cs.CV) techniques. The paper also mentions the importance of feature-driven methods for in situ data analysis, which could fall under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the proposed Residual Autoencoder integrated Residual in Residual Dense Block (RRDB) involves neural networks (cs.NE) and deep learning techniques.
